DOSBox demoscene compat testing chart
Ref: ftp://ftp.scene.org
Demoscene testing repository: https://github.com/joncampbell123/demotest

DOSBox-X refers to the DOSBox-X project
DOSBox-SVN refers to the DOSBox project
DOSBox-X-DOS refers to the DOSBox-X project booting an MS-DOS system.
DOSBox-SVN-DOS refers to the DOSBox project booting an MS-DOS system.
Bochs-SVN refers to the Bochs project booting an MS-DOS system disk.
QEMU refers to the QEMU project booting an MS-DOS system disk.

Rules regarding PASS or FAIL:
- If a demo crashes, faults, or shows behavior that suggests a problem, that is a FAIL.
- Known faulty behavior in the demo itself doesn't count as failure. Future development may offer off-by-default hacks or workarounds in the emulator for the problem.
- Known faulty behavior that occurs on real hardware doesn't count as failure, because it means DOSBox is emulating real hardware accurately and the demo is at fault.
- Issues that are DOSBox-SVN's fault, that the DOSBox SVN developers have expressed an unwillingness to fix or accept patches to fix, do not count as failure.

Common problems with DOSBox SVN so far:
- Lack of support for "goldplay" Sound Blaster playback. Audio is rendered "muffled" in DOSBox SVN. So far this is not relevant to DOS games, and may be re-marked as a failure that doesn't count against SVN.
- LPT DAC output doesn't work. However code explicitly written for the Disney Sound Source works.
- PC speaker emulation on/off and frequency changes are limited to 1ms precision. This affects some demos as well as old Apogee titles like Duke Nukum.
- Some demos rely on INT 16h AH=1 undefined behavior regarding ZF flag (standard only describes CF flag), which so far has been confirmed on at least one 386 system and may occur in other old systems.

Common problems to both DOSBox-X and DOSBox-SVN:
- Having UMB or EMS enabled can cause crashiness in some demos.
- Some demos require XMS to be enabled, will call to a NULL pointer otherwise.
- Some demos will crash or malfunction if loaded too low (below 64KB) in memory. Try loadfix or the minimum mcb segment option.

Problems that do NOT count as failures against DOSBox SVN, because they are bugs in the demo itself:
- Audio halting or interrupt problems with GUS or SB related to a failure to unmask the IRQ (democoder laziness, NOT SVN's fault).
- Hangs related to undefined or reserved bits in VGA emulation that the demo really ought to ignore.

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
Important notes:
- Sound Blaster output: DO NOT specify a sample rate higher than 20KHz. The demo will send Direct DAC output at the rate you specify. It will not wait for DSP ready, and it will not cap the sample rate within range. It will crash at higher than 25KHz sample rates.

DOSBox-SVN NOTES:

- Disney Sound Source / LPT DAC output doesn't work

- Sound Blaster output: DO NOT specify a sample rate higher than 20KHz. The demo will send Direct DAC output at the rate you specify. It will not wait for DSP ready, and it will not cap the sample rate within range. It will crash at higher than 25KHz sample rates.

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
Demo bugs:
- When the demo probes the Sound Blaster IRQ, it uses a software timeout
(I/O delay) that can fail to detect the IRQ if it takes longer than
500ns for it's IRQ handler to receive the signal.
- If the demo cannot detect the Sound Blaster IRQ, then it will take
IRQ 0 (the timer interrupt) as the Sound Blaster IRQ, which will then
result in incorrect music playback.
PASSPASS------------mirrors/hornet/demos/1994/f/fdintro.zip
PASSPASS------------mirrors/hornet/demos/1994/f/fdreams.zip

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
Notes:
- Sound Blaster Pro support will hang, playing garbage data, if the demo also detected a Gravis Ultrasound,
however at least it will also default to the Gravis Ultrasound if you hit enter.
- Sound Blaster Pro support starts with a 1-byte DMA buffer, which falsely triggers DOSBox-X's goldplay mode,
and let that play until the demo is ready to run, but the demo will change the DMA base count to the final
length later when running.
- If you select "Sound Blaster 16" you must specify the 16-bit DMA channel (usually 5)
or the demo will not play any music.
Real hardware:
- Toshiba 1997 Pentium with SBPro compatible OPL3-SAx: Sound Blaster Pro support works perfectly fine, does not hang as described above. However the 3D maze runs too fast, and exhibits Mode X tearlines.
- COMP-Old486y91, GUS, PAS: GUS support works fine. SBPro selection detected the PAS and refused, properly.

Why the demo failed the test:
- Demo hangs if attempting to use Gravis Ultrasound

DOSBox-SVN NOTES: 
Why the demo failed the test:
- DOSBox SVN does not emulate undocumented INT 16h AH=1 behavior where the BIOS sets CF and ZF to specific values, which this demo requires to "sense" keyboard input. Such behavior has been confirmed with older (1992-ish) 386 BIOSes.

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
Gravis Ultrasound support DOES NOT WORK
May crash during wavy rotating graphic if less than 610-620K-ish of RAM.
VERY picky about the amount of available memory! Less than 615KB or so and some parts fail outright.
More than 620KB risks the effects inherent in running DOS applications too low in memory.
Unstable demo code.
Killed the keyboard on return to DOS??
PASSFAIL------------parties/1994/assembly94/demo/myth-dw.zip
* This is a known duplicate of mirrors/hornet/demos/1994/m/myth_dw.zip

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
Notes:
- Sound Blaster Pro support will hang, playing garbage data, if the demo also detected a Gravis Ultrasound,
however at least it will also default to the Gravis Ultrasound if you hit enter.
- Sound Blaster Pro support starts with a 1-byte DMA buffer, which falsely triggers DOSBox-X's goldplay mode,
and let that play until the demo is ready to run, but the demo will change the DMA base count to the final
length later when running.
- If you select "Sound Blaster 16" you must specify the 16-bit DMA channel (usually 5)
or the demo will not play any music.
Real hardware:
- Toshiba 1997 Pentium with SBPro compatible OPL3-SAx: Sound Blaster Pro support works perfectly fine, does not hang as described above. However the 3D maze runs too fast, and exhibits Mode X tearlines.
- COMP-Old486y91, GUS, PAS: GUS support works fine. SBPro selection detected the PAS and refused, properly.

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
Demo bugs:
- When the demo probes the Sound Blaster IRQ, it uses a software timeout
(I/O delay) that can fail to detect the IRQ if it takes longer than
500ns for it's IRQ handler to receive the signal.
- If the demo cannot detect the Sound Blaster IRQ, then it will take
IRQ 0 (the timer interrupt) as the Sound Blaster IRQ, which will then
result in incorrect music playback.
PASSPASS------------parties/1994/bizarre94/demo/prologue.zip
* This is a known duplicate of mirrors/hornet/demos/1994/p/prologue.zip

Why the demo failed the test:
- Music plays way too fast (unless that's intentional??).
! Please check against real hardware
TEST RESULTS:
- Inconclusive: Chips & Tech 65554 SVGA laptop. Not having EMM386.EXE loaded results in "not enough memory for samples" on a laptop with 32MB of memory. Right.
- Inconclusive: S3 VIRGE PCI SVGA. EMM386.EXE is resident. System does not have GUS, but has Sound Blaster 16, which plays at normal speed.
- FAIL. Running IPLAY.EXE in DOSBox-X but selecting Sound Blaster 16 instead of Gravis Ultrasound gives very normal playback. Gravis Ultrasound playback is WAY TOO FAST.
- FAIL. Running IPLAY.EXE in DOSBox-X but selecting Sound Blaster Pro instead of Gravis Ultrasound causes audio playback at 200% speed (and audio is higher pitched as well) unless you specifically set a mixing rate of 44KHz. Gravis Ultrasound playback is WAY TOO FAST.

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
Why the demo failed the test:
- Demo misrenders title, screen is garbled, bad bank switching support code.
- Uses A0000 to C7FFF as if a linear framebuffer (???)
- Calls VESA BIOS to set mode 0x101 non-linear framebuffer
- Appears to draw to the screen as if a linear frame-buffer starting at A0000 (????!?)
- Does not appear to pay attention to the Linear Framebuffer availabilitiy flag
- Does not appear to support window/bank switching
- Talks to VESA BIOS as if VBE1.1 (does not write VESA signature on query), allocated buffer is 256 bytes (512 byte struct would overrun adjacent text)
! PLEASE RUN THIS ON REAL HARDWARE AND EXAMINE BEHAVIOR TO DETERMINE WHERE IT WORKS AND DOESN'T WORK

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
- Horrible demo! (on purpose?)
- Here's a big gotcha about the Sound Blaster menu:
It expects you to type in the whole port number. Not just the middle
digit like most demos, and not just "220" because that becomes decimal.
No, you must enter the port number like "$220" (Turbo Pascal version of
hexadecimal). The program does not range-check the port number, so if
you enter say "$170" you can direct Sound Blaster output at your secondary
IDE controller :)

DOSBox-X & DOSBox-SVN NOTES: 
Why the demo failed the test:
- Demo runs, displays "guns" and rotating object, then crashes.
- One likely reason the demo crashes is that it cannot load some of
it's files. Some files in the DATA directory do not fit into the
8.3 filename limit, suggesting that this DOS demo is intended
to run in a DOS box under Windows 95/98 since there does exist an
API to access "Long Filenames" from DOS within Windows 95/98.
Getting this demo to run may require implementation of Long
Filenames.

PASSFAIL------------parties/1999/volcanic99/demo/m-evo.zip

DOSBox-X NOTES: 
- Demo menu claims to support 32bpp, but does not. It does not actually query available
VESA modes but assumes mode numbers. 32bpp will always answer that it was not found.
24bpp will assume mode 0x10F which on most cards is 32bpp and will not display properly.

DOSBox-SVN NOTES: 
Why the demo failed the test:
- Demo only supports 24bpp VESA mode 0x10F, which DOSBox SVN does not provide.
